# blocked.md — the backward crossing (example)

> The loop writes this file when it hits something it **cannot verify its way out of** — a real
> decision the spec doesn't settle, or a task that won't go green. Writing here is how a *realization*
> loop re-enters *reflection* (human territory) instead of guessing (ADR 0027 §3). Each blocker is one
> `##` section, appended; a human triages it → re-decompose the task, decide it (often an **ADR**, which
> makes the next loop run smarter), or fix it interactively. The loop leaves the task **unchecked** in
> `TODO.md` and moves on.

This is an **example** of the shape. A live `blocked.md` lives at the project root next to `TODO.md`.

---

## Task: Add a `max_length` truncation option to `slugify`

**Status**: BLOCKED (maker, iteration 3) — implicit decision, not mine to make.

**The decision the spec doesn't settle**: when a slug exceeds `max_length`, where do we cut?
- (a) Hard-cut at exactly `max_length` characters — may leave a trailing hyphen or split a word
      (`"hello-world"` → `"hello-wo"`).
- (b) Cut at the last hyphen boundary at or before `max_length` — never splits a word
      (`"hello-world"` → `"hello"`), but can return far fewer characters than asked.
- (c) Hard-cut, then strip any trailing hyphen (`"hello-world"` → `"hello-wo"` stays, `"hello-"` → `"hello"`).

These produce **different observable outputs** for the same input, and the acceptance test does not
pin it down. Picking one silently would bake a product decision into a loop commit.

**Why I won't guess**: this is a behaviour choice a user will depend on; it belongs in reflection (an
ADR or a sharpened task), not in an autonomous maker turn. Truncation also interacts with the existing
"collapse and trim hyphens" rule — order matters — which compounds the ambiguity.

**What would unblock me**:
- A task line that states the rule explicitly (e.g. "truncate at the last hyphen ≤ max_length, then
  trim a trailing hyphen"), **or**
- An ADR deciding the truncation semantics, referenced from the task.

**Suggested triage**: decide → ADR (truncation is a small but real product semantic), then re-add the
task with the rule inlined and an acceptance test that pins the chosen behaviour.
